                <head>101. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On July 23, 1962, Director of the National Reconnaissance Office <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJV1">Joseph V. Charyk</persName> sent a memorandum to <gloss
                        target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss> Program Directors and the Director of the
                        <gloss target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss> Staff setting forth the “Organization
                    and Functions of the <gloss target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss>.” The memorandum
                    established the basic organization of the <gloss target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss>,
                    described the functions of the elements, and outlined the concept and operation.
                    After a discussion of the sensitivity of the <gloss target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss>
                    mission and the necessity for concealing the organization behind “plausible,
                    overt” names, the memorandum described the responsibilities of the directors of
                    the three elements: “Director, Program A being responsible for <gloss
                        target="#t_NRP1">NRP</gloss> satellite effort conducted by the <gloss
                        target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss> through utilization of Department of the Air
                    Force resources, and the Director, Program B being responsible for <gloss
                        target="#t_NRP1">NRP</gloss> effort conducted by the <gloss target="#t_NRO1"
                        >NRO</gloss> through utilization of Central Intelligence Agency resources. A
                    Director, Program C is being established to be responsible for <gloss
                        target="#t_NRP1">NRP</gloss> effort conducted by the <gloss target="#t_NRO1"
                        >NRO</gloss> through utilization of Naval Research Laboratory resources.”
                    The <gloss target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss> Staff was responsible for assisting the
                    Director, coordination and liaison with the U.S. Intelligence Board and the
                    principal consumers of the intelligence collected, and overall management and
                    monitoring of projects and staff. (National Reconnaissance Office, <gloss
                        target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss> Office of Policy Files) <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJV1">Charyk</persName>’s memorandum, along with organization
                    charts of the National Reconnaissance Office and the <gloss target="#t_NRO1"
                        >NRO</gloss> Staff, is available on the Internet, National Security Archive
                    (www.gwu.edu/-~-nsarchiv), Electronic Briefing Book No. 35, “The <gloss
                        target="#t_NRO1">NRO</gloss> Declassified,” <ref target="#d6">Document
                        6</ref>.</p>
